$GOOGL Cloud took over a decade to reach $10B in ARR.

It added the next $10B in just six months.

The past six months moved faster than the first decade and it shows how quickly the AI economy is compounding.

Bill Gates says AI is the biggest technical shift of his lifetime.

Hard to overstate that coming from someone who lived through the PC and internet eras.

This past week was huge for the AI Utility theme. 

The hyperscaler earnings all pointed to one thing that demand is running ahead of power, racks & chips which directly sets up the next leg for independent AI compute providers.

$AMZN showed AWS re-accelerating to 20% growth on a $132B run rate with backlog near $200B. They added 3.8 gigawatts of power in the last year and expect to double again by 2027. Every megawatt that isnâ€™t delivered by AWS on time gets filled by third-party GPU infrastructure.

$MSFT said AI capacity will grow 80% this year & their entire data center footprint will double in two years. They're capacity constrained through FY26 even after spending $35B on CapEx last quarter which means demand is spilling into non-hyperscaler compute providers that can deploy faster or cheaper.

$GOOGL Cloud backlog hit $155B, up 40% sequentially & management said they remain supply constrained through 2026. Thatâ€™s an admission that the AI buildout is outpacing the speed at which power, silicon & data centers can come online.

$META raised CapEx to $71B for 2025 & said 2026 will be â€œnotably larger.â€ Theyâ€™re renting external GPU capacity while building their own which validates the economics of independent GPU providers who can offer compute to hyperscalers themselves.

This is the moment where specialized infrastructure players pick up share:

â€¢ $CRWV high-density GPU cloud built for AI training at scale

â€¢ $WULF baseload compute in the lowest-cost energy regions

â€¢ $NBIS enterprise GPU clusters offering compute without hyperscaler lock-in

The next phase of AI infra belongs to whoever can deploy compute the fastest & most efficiently per megawatt.

People keep yelling â€œbubbleâ€ every time the market makes a new high but bubbles happen when prices disconnect from fundamentals.

Thatâ€™s not whatâ€™s happening here. Earnings keep beating expectations, margins are expanding & companies are getting more efficient while multiples are even compressing as prices move higher. 

I keep coming back to the PEG ratio because it adjusts valuation for how fast earnings are growing. Right now the $SPY PEG ratio is ~1.3 which means valuations are tracking growth in a responsible way. In 2021, during the last real bubble, it was over 2 because prices were running way ahead of fundamentals.
